Exploring Bay Wheels Trip Data¶

by Petra Schneckenburger¶

Preliminary Wrangling¶

Bay Wheels is a regional public bicycle sharing system in the San Francisco Bay Area, California. It was established as Bay Area Bike Share in August 2013. 2017, the system officially re-launched as Ford GoBike in a partnership with Ford Motor Company and After acquisition by Lyft, the system was renamed to Bay Wheels in June 2019. Bay Wheels is the first regional and large-scale bicycle sharing system deployed in California and on the West Coast of the United States.

The bicycles are available 24 hours a day, seven days a week for periods ranging from a single ride (up to 30 minutes) to a day pass, in 30-minute increments, or customers can purchase an annual subscription which gives them unlimited rides up to 45-minutes in duration. A reduced pricing option called "Bike Share for All" exists for users who qualify for CalFresh, the SFMTA's Lifeline pass, or PG & E's CARE discount. This membership option provides rides of 60 minutes without an additional charge.

The used dataset consists of trip dates from January 2018 until July 2019. It provides informations about the start and end stations of the trips, start and end times of the trips, informations of the users as gender and birth year and the kind of user membership. The trip data can be downloaded from https://www.lyft.com/bikes/bay-wheels/system-data

# extracting zipfiles and creating dataframes
frames = []
for file in os.listdir('data2'):

    zf = zipfile.ZipFile(f'data2/{file}')
    df = pd.read_csv(zf.open(file[:-4]))
    frames.append(df)

# calculating member age

def calc_age(time, birth_year):
    if time[:4] == '2018':
        return 2018 - birth_year
    else:
        return 2019 - birth_year

# calculating distance between stations
# https://stackoverflow.com/questions/19412462/getting-distance-between-two-points-based-on-latitude-longitude
import geopy
from geopy.distance import geodesic

def get_distance(start_lat, start_long, end_lat, end_long):
    
    origin = (start_lat, start_long)  # (latitude, longitude) don't confuse
    dist = (end_lat, end_long)
    return geodesic(origin, dist).kilometers

data_clean['distance_km'] = data_clean.apply(lambda x: get_distance(x['start_station_latitude'], x['start_station_longitude'], x['end_station_latitude'], x['end_station_longitude']), axis=1)

What is the structure of your dataset?¶

The dataset consist of 3059980 rows and data in 17 columns. There are informations about the date and time the bikes were used, the start and end stations and their locations, the ids of the bikes, informations about distance and duration of trips and data about the users as age, gender and membership . The data are stretching over 19 months.

What is/are the main feature(s) of interest in your dataset?¶

For the first exploration steps I had no special intentions, just wanted to look on several variables to get aquainted with the data. But it will be interesting to see when these bikes were used and who uses them.

What features in the dataset do you think will help support your investigation into your feature(s) of interest?¶

Especially data of start and end times as well as user data will be helpful

In [47]:
# setting regions as new variables because they are more handy than coordinates
def region(long):
    if long > -122:
        return('San Jose')
    elif long > -122.35:
        return('East Bay')
    else:
        return('San Francisco')

data['start_region'] = data.start_station_longitude.apply(lambda x: region(x))
data['end_region'] = data.end_station_longitude.apply(lambda x: region(x))

# setting age bins
# 18 to 30, 31 to 40, 41 to 50, 51 to 60, 61 to 70, 71 to 80

def grouping_age(x):
    if 18<=x<30:
        return('18-29')
    elif 30<=x<40:
        return('30-39')
    elif 40<=x<50:
        return('40-49')
    elif 50<=x<60:
        return('50-59')
    else:
        return('60-79')
    
data['age_group'] = data.member_age.apply(lambda x: grouping_age(x))

Discuss the distribution(s) of your variable(s) of interest. Were there any unusual points? Did you need to perform any transformations?¶

  • The distribution of distance is heavily right skewed. For the display, the x-axis was limited.
  • The distribution of duration also is heavily right skewed. Here, the x-axis was transformed to log scale for better display.
  • examining daily and hourly counts of bike trips revealed some interesting patterns that are worth to be investigated more

Of the features you investigated, were there any unusual distributions? Did you perform any operations on the data to tidy, adjust, or change the form of the data? If so, why did you do this?¶

I did several changes to the raw data:

  • There were not valid and missing data in member_birth_year. These were omitted in the cleaning section.
  • There were not valid and missing data in the station columns. These rows also were removed in the cleaning section.
  • For better usage, I calculated a distance column from the station coordinates, as well as extracted time data as year, year_month, weekday and hour from the start_time data.

# split datframe in customer_data and subscriber_data
customer_data = data[data.user_type == 'Customer']
subscriber_data = data[data.user_type == 'Subscriber']

#calculating percentage of total  trips for  each group and pivoting data
customer_props = customer_data.groupby(['hour', 'weekday']).size()/customer_data.shape[0]*100

customer_props = customer_props.pivot(index = 'hour', columns = 'weekday', values = 'count')

subscriber_props = subscriber_props.pivot(index = 'hour', columns = 'weekday', values = 'count')

g.legend(loc='center left', bbox_to_anchor=(1, 0.1), ncol=1);

# https://stackoverflow.com/questions/53733755/how-to-move-legend-to-outside-of-a-seaborn-scatterplot
  • here we can clearly see that over all days of week the customer take longer trips than the subscriber
  • the median trip duration of subscribers doesn't change over the week, whereas the median trip duration of the customer group is higher on weekends than on working days.
  • this supports the findig that customers use the bikes also for leisure, maybe for longer trips or sports on weekends, whereas on working days there were more short trips probably directly to or from work

Talk about some of the relationships you observed in this part of the investigation. Were there features that strengthened each other in terms of looking at your feature(s) of interest?¶

  • In the heatmaps of the usage distribution separated for customers and subscribers we can see, that the bike usage seen on weekends comes more from the the customers, while in the rushours on working days both user types contribute to the seen peaking patterns.
  • Summarizing the findings of trip duration and trip starting times pattern we can conclude that the subscriber group mostly takes the bike to go to and from work, while the customer group uses bikes for the way to and from work as well as for other purposes in free times.

Were there any interesting or surprising interactions between features?¶

It was surprising that not also the time usage but also the trip durations differences between the user types can be seen so clearly.
